Nov 18, 2019

Motivation

  • Does severe asthma exacerbation have any effect on subsequent severe asthma exacerbations and mortality?
  • This question with COPD has been studied recently (Suissa, DellAniello, and Ernst 2012) with an approporiate method (Sadatsafavi et al. 2018).
  • The purpose of my term project is to understand the methodology used in Sadatsafavi et al. (2018), and apply it to available datasets, which are clinical datasets on COPD.

Outline

  1. COPD datasets
  2. Recurrent events and a terminal event
  3. Covariates
  4. Joint/shared frailty model
  5. Results

What is Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)?

  • COPD is characterized by coughing and shortness of breath, usually caused by two mechanisms: 1) damaged alveoli 2) damaged bronchial tubes.
  • An excerbation is a sudden worsening or flare-up of the COPD symtoms. It could take a month or longer to recover completely from it. (Nation-Jewish-Health n.d.)

MACRO and OPTIMAL Clinical Datasets

  • The data is composed of two randomized clinical datasets: MACRO (Albert et al. 2011) and OPTIMAL (Aaron et al. 2007).
  • For each trial, there is a control group (placebo) and treatment groups (drugs).
  • The response variable in these studies is the exacerbation rate, defined as the number of COPD exacerbations per year. Note that there are different levels of COPD excerbation (mild and severe).
  • The purpose of these studies is to investigate the effects of drugs on excerbation rate.

Cumulative Sample Mean (CSM)

CSM(t)=\(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n N_i(t),\) where \(N_i(t)=\)# of events of interest over the time interval \([0,t]\) for patient \(i\) (Cook and Lawless 2007).

Why Joint Modeling?

  • We see that the follow-up of the patients was terminated by death, meaning that any subsequent severe COPD exacerbation cannot occur.
  • The exploratory data analysis shows that death could be correlated with severe COPD exacerbations; the recurrence of severe COPD exacerbations could increase the risk of death.
  • Joint/shared frailty (random effects) models allow one to study the two processes together.

Frailty Models

  • Proportional Cox hazard models are frailty models without random effects: \[\lambda_{ij}(t)= \lambda_0(t) \exp(\beta^T X_{ij}),\] where \(\lambda_0(\cdot)\) is the baseline hazard function.

  • Adding random effects, you get a (gamma) frailty model: \[\lambda_{ij}(t|v_i)= \lambda_0(t) \exp(\beta^T X_{ij}+\log(v_i)),\] where \(v_i \sim^d \Gamma(1/\theta,1/\theta)\) are i.i.d. Note that that \(E(v_i)=1\) and \(Var(v_i)=\theta\).

  • Under this specification, the likelihood has an analytical form (Cook and Lawless 2007).

Joint/shared Frailty models

  • A joint frailty model of the recurrent events (RE) and a terminal event is characterized by two hazard functions: \[\mbox{(RE) } r_{ij}(s|v_i) = v_i r_0(s) \exp(\beta_r^T X_{ij})\] and \[ \mbox{(death) } \lambda_{i}(t|v_i) = v_i^\alpha \lambda_0(t) \exp(\beta_d^T X_{i}), ~\alpha \geq 0.\]
  • \(s\) is the gaptime; \(s_{ij}=T_{ij}-T_{i(j-1)}, T_{i0}=0\) for patient \(i\) and \(j\)th gaptime.
  • Notice that the frailty term, \(v_i\), is shared by the two processes.

Meaning of the frailty term

  • The dependence in this model is characterized by \((\alpha,\theta)\).
  • Suppose \(\theta\) is not null (if it is, then two processes are independent and \(\alpha\) has no meaning).
  • If \(\alpha=0\), then there is no dependence attributable to unobserved covariates (i.e.no depedence given observed covariates).
  • If \(\alpha>0\), then \(\theta\) not only accounts for heterogeniety in patients but describes the dependence (attributable to unobserved covariates) between the two processes through \(\alpha\).

Choice of Baseline Hazard Functions and \(v_i\)

  • There are many choices available for frailty models but not so many for shared frailty models. Likelihood of the shared fraitly models does not have an analytical form.
  • I experimented with several packages in R and SAS; they have different estimation methods.
  • For joint frailty models, I tried frailtypack (Rondeau et al. 2007) in R and the approach using NLMIXED in SAS by Liu and Huang (2008) (this is the approach taken by Sadatsafavi et al. (2018)).
  • Rondeau et al. (2007) proposed a numerical method for frailty and shared frailty models with nonparametric hazard functions (using splines) with the gamma frailty.
  • Liu and Huang (2008) proposed the use of Gaussian quadrature for parametric (standard Weibull) and piece-wise hazard functions in frailty and shared frailty models. In this framework, \(v_i\) can chosen more flexibly (through transformation techniques). I used Normal(0,\(\sigma^2\)) in addition to the standard gamma frailty.

  • To check the validity of those two methods , I also used parfm (Munda et al. 2012) in R for parametric hazard functions (Weibull) with the gamma frailty in simple frailty models.
  • Note that for parametric hazard functions, using the gamma frailty leads to an analytical form of the likelihood (Cook and Lawless 2007); standard optimzation techniques can be used to estimate the parameters.
  • I ran into errors when I used frailtypack for shared frailty models It has many practical barriers.

SAS Code

# PROC NLMIXED DATA=WORK.copd GCONV=0 QPOINTS=6 GTOL=1E-8 COV CORR;
#   PARMS /* Initial values for the parameters */
#   lin=b_0+...+b_p X_p + z;
#   alpha=EXP(lin);
#   S_t=exp(-(alpha*gaptime)**EXP(ln_gamma));
#   h=EXP(ln_gamma)*alpha*((gaptime*alpha)**(EXP(ln_gamma)-1));
#   ll1=(recurrent_event~=1)*log(S_t)+(recurrent_event=1)*log(h*S_t);
#   lin_d=b_d_0 +   ... + d_q X_q + z/kinv;
#   alpha_d=EXP(lin_d);
#   S_t_d=exp(-(alpha_d*gaptime)**EXP(ln_gamma_d));
#   h_d=EXP(ln_gamma_d)*alpha_d*((gaptime*alpha_d)**(EXP(ln_gamma_d)-1));
#   ll2=(death~=1)*log(S_t_d)+(death=1)*log(h_d*S_t_d);
#   ll=ll1+ll2;
#   MODEL gaptime~general(ll);
#   RANDOM z~NORMAL(0,EXP(ln_v)) SUBJECT=ID;
